29:19.742 --> 29:21.244
Getting a little low on tape, we'll turn it over. 
Okay, let's just change it up a little bit and talk

29:21.524 --> 29:26.110
about chemical weapons. Okay. I know you work with 
chemical weapons now. I work with Defense Against

29:31.137 --> 29:33.300
Chemical Weapons. Defense Against Chemical 
Weapons. Okay. You know something about them. Why

29:37.205 --> 29:37.866
don't you... Tell me about some different types of 
chemicals used in Vietnam and what the purposes

29:38.369 --> 29:43.414
were. Well, we'd first off have to define 
chemical, but if you consider napalm a chemical,

29:43.434 --> 29:52.104
that was used on occasion, used in flamethrowers 
also. By the way, the North Vietnamese had good

29:52.564 --> 29:54.687
flamethrowers. They cooked a bunch of villagers 
just south of my base one time.

30:01.194 --> 30:07.060
They didn't have the planes down there to deliver 
the napalm, but an individual spraying it kills

30:01.194 --> 30:07.060
them just as dead, maybe not as many. But getting 
into the chemicals, CS gas mostly, kind of a

30:08.255 --> 30:19.290
powerful tear gas. They used it, we used it. The 
other chemical we used was at that time called

30:22.794 --> 30:29.403
defoliant, and I heard the term Agent Orange 
between tours. First tour when we had it, it was

30:29.423 --> 30:31.866
simply called defoliant. It had an orange thing on 
top of the barrel, so that's where it got its name.

30:38.596 --> 30:39.917
We weren't trained in its use. We were told to put it 
in these tanks and go out and spray it on the trees

30:40.037 --> 30:46.183
around the fire bases and clear the fire bases. 
Now, the Air Force Ranch Hand Program was clear in

30:46.223 --> 30:48.566
the jungle. We were just clearing 500-meter 
strips around fire bases with it. Basically, a

30:53.110 --> 30:58.916
mixture of 2,4-D and 2,4-5-T, which is used in our 
rice country. 2,4-D is used, 2,4-5-T, but they're

31:00.597 --> 31:04.021
not used full strength. The problem is in the 
manufacture of this agent during the war, they

31:09.443 --> 31:12.906
left out a key quality control step. As they were 
running it through, the process dioxin buildup

31:12.926 --> 31:19.393
occurs. And the dioxin could be as small as five 
parts per billion. Or in some cases, they've

31:27.380 --> 31:30.944
analyzed barrels of it and found it as high. And 
this is not generally published, to my knowledge,

31:31.104 --> 31:35.248
168 parts per million. which means it's extremely 
toxic. And because of the shoddy quality control

31:39.027 --> 32:01.641
done by the chemical manufacturer and the United 
States government, we sprayed a poison that had

31:39.027 --> 32:01.641
been considered safe when it was used as 2,4-D and 
2,4-5-T. Because in the manufacturing process

31:39.027 --> 32:01.641
for the government, they left out those quality 
control steps that allowed the dioxin buildup.

32:02.566 --> 32:05.951
Dioxin is one of the byproducts of this 
manufacturer, as I understand it. I'm not

32:05.991 --> 32:07.413
completely familiar with that. But that 
particular piece was shoddy manufacturing

32:08.375 --> 32:13.122
processes. And as a result, no one really thought 
it was that harmful. But one of us always wore a gas

32:17.488 --> 32:24.018
mask when we were spraying it, just in case the tank 
was ruptured and the stuff came around. And I've

32:24.158 --> 32:28.866
seen it come, you know, take the paint off the tail 
boom of my helicopter. And I've come back with My

32:31.827 --> 32:39.537
uniform saturated with the stuff because we flew 
with the doors open and the windows open and stuff

32:31.827 --> 32:39.537
like that when we were dropping, so you'd fly back 
through your own mist a lot of times. We would empty

32:40.458 --> 32:54.797
that same container, put spray in it, DDT, and go 
spray the troops for mosquito control. We were our

32:55.418 --> 33:00.484
own worst enemies in chemical warfare there 
because we sprayed our own troops. We never

33:00.504 --> 33:01.665
sprayed Charlie. Occasionally, if we had any 
left, we would go out and spray Charlie's rice

33:01.866 --> 33:24.092
crop, where the intelligence officer had told us 
to, but that was about two or three missions, and we

33:01.866 --> 33:24.092
found we were getting fired at so bad, and we had 
slicks at the time, not gunships, we carried these

33:01.866 --> 33:24.092
tanks in, that we told the chemical officer and the 
intelligence officer that if they wanted that

33:01.866 --> 33:24.092
damn stuff dropped, on those farms out there, then 
they were going to have to provide gunship escort

33:24.713 --> 33:29.799
because those farmers didn't want their rice 
crops to break. And so we didn't go do that very

33:31.581 --> 33:34.905
often after that.

33:39.310 --> 33:47.259
Chemicals, I had several experiences with tear 
gas, ours and theirs, ours being some of our troops

33:39.310 --> 33:47.259
would toss tear gas. We had tear gas in the 
perimeter. Lightning would hit during the

33:50.863 --> 33:53.826
monsoon. and set off several containers of tear 
gas, or these containers would fire tear gas out.

34:03.070 --> 34:03.931
Those would go off. Several claymore mines would 
go off. Occasionally, a thing called fugas, which

34:05.774 --> 34:09.459
is a napalm mixture, would go off. Now, the other 
chemical agent that was used was phosphorus,

34:10.080 --> 34:14.106
white phosphorus. Used them as smoke shells to 
mark artillery rounds. That's what we used for

34:19.153 --> 34:20.235
spotter. And God help the poor son of a gun that got 
phosphorus on him. If our artillery was accurate

34:23.464 --> 34:28.031
on him at the first round, then he really got hurt. 
As far as this chemical warfare of germ warfare

34:30.375 --> 34:43.817
agents, as far as chemical warfare in the terms of 
poison gases, those were not used, at least not to

34:30.375 --> 34:43.817
my knowledge. And I've never found anyone who 
knows they were. That goes back to the Korean War.

34:49.426 --> 34:53.610
when the Chinese sanitary conditions were 
causing such tremendous losses among their

34:49.426 --> 34:53.610
forces. Their propaganda was, it's not us that's 
doing it. It's the germ warfare of the Americans

34:59.156 --> 35:03.080
and the chemical warfare of the Americans. The 
people who've used chemical warfare, I'm talking

35:04.141 --> 35:11.229
about lethal agents, have been the Soviets. Our 
army is still to this day not geared to do it. That's

35:14.772 --> 35:18.336
why I'm working to try to build a defense for it. You 
don't use the stuff if you can't defend yourself

35:19.227 --> 35:24.252
against it, your own stuff. But the Soviet army has 
always been able to do that, and all of their

35:24.272 --> 35:29.797
surrogate states have, and as a result, around the 
world. Since 1963 in Yemen, with the Soviet

35:30.598 --> 35:39.946
surrogates of the day, Egypt, they've used lethal 
agents, primarily mustard and carbon. That's

35:40.066 --> 35:42.789
blister gas and nerve gas. So that's the sum total 
of my chemical warfare. In Vietnam, we used tear

35:48.488 --> 35:50.130
gas a lot. We would use tear gas to run them out of 
caves. We would use tear gas to flush them out of

35:53.375 --> 35:59.863
villages and bunkers near villages. And to me, 
using tear gas on a village to flush people out and

36:01.405 --> 36:11.919
try to catch them is a lot more humane than going in 
and putting napalm on the whole damn village.

36:13.201 --> 36:17.567
Because sooner or later, you've got to make a 
decision of how many more men are going to die

36:13.201 --> 36:17.567
because of that machine gun nest. When that 
decision's made, you're going to take out that

36:19.184 --> 36:24.091
machine gun nest or you're going to quit that pipe, 
one of the two. Were the benefits of using

36:26.274 --> 36:28.958
chemicals that great in Vietnam? I mean, looking 
back on it now compared to the past. Looking back on

36:30.660 --> 36:37.270
it, I ended up with soft tissue tumor, as you well 
know, and I laid a lot of it back to the dioxin. But I

36:37.290 --> 36:39.673
think We started using it, well, the high command, 
I'm sure, started using defoliants to defoliate

36:41.813 --> 36:50.584
problem areas that they would take tremendous 
casualties in. The Iron Triangle was practically

36:51.445 --> 36:53.748
all defoliated. That was the Ranch Hand Project. 
They went in after that and used their own plows to

36:55.751 --> 37:05.544
knock down the sticks because these were hiding 
places for the enemy units that were threatening

36:55.751 --> 37:05.544
Saigon. In our area where it was used, it was used to 
clear... areas around the fire bases. And this

37:13.524 --> 37:16.788
wasn't used around every fire base, depending on 
how long they planned to stay there. Around Chia

37:16.808 --> 37:22.276
Rio, for instance, is where I used a lot of it to 
clear two or three places around Chia Rio. And it

37:23.417 --> 37:27.022
was very effective. It meant that that unit had a 
clear field where they could have some hope of

37:27.283 --> 37:33.251
seeing. You have to understand the North 
Vietnamese soldier was a very good jungle

37:33.872 --> 37:38.398
fighter. By that I mean he was a master at 
camouflage. He lived in that damn jungle and our

37:43.559 --> 37:46.123
people didn't. And he could move through that 
jungle very quietly, very patiently when he

37:47.665 --> 37:51.530
wanted to. And so with our policy of building these 
little fire bases, miniature forts, The

37:59.303 --> 38:07.162
perimeter of that fort quotes or the outpost 50 
meters away was the outer line of defense. And if

38:07.182 --> 38:17.667
that outer line of defense, if you've only cleaned 
out that one area and your outer line of defense now

38:07.182 --> 38:17.667
stops at brush and scrub 20 and 30 feet high. You've 
left an area there where you have an entire

38:18.727 --> 38:24.215
regiment crawl upon you before you even know 
they're there. So we cleared these fields of fire,

38:24.636 --> 38:28.241
these areas around the bases. And so I think it was 
very good. I blame our own people, whether they are

38:30.144 --> 38:42.363
engineers in the chemical companies or whether 
they are purchasing people in the US government

38:30.144 --> 38:42.363
for allowing the dioxin buildup. They never 
allowed that combination to go to the commercial

38:47.887 --> 38:56.416
farmer without checking that step in the quality 
control process yet, just because they were going

38:47.887 --> 38:56.416
to drop it on the enemy in the jungle. They never 
made that check. And the dioxin buildup is causing

39:00.099 --> 39:04.984
casualties to this day in some people, I believe.

39:09.849 --> 39:10.410
OK.

